  Myasthenia gravis is an neuromuscular disorder, whereas pathogenesis is an autoimmune phenomen. Nowadays thymectomy has much impact on patients follow up and has to be indicated early after diagnosis when stabilization of disease has been achieved. Radical resection of the thymus gland and ectopic tissue is mandatory for surgical sucess and improvement of the disease. Opening of both chest cavities can be helpful in operative strategy, especially for exstirpation of thymic tumors. Various maior, minor or minimal invasive surgical techniques and access are possible for thymus surgery, whereas we propagate an extended thymectomy via a complete median sternotomy.  
